title: Great for a project still in alpha
comment: A little help for the people who can not find or run their downloaded games; Any games archived as .7z, .rar, or .zip need to be extracted. The most organized way to do this is make a folder named dolphin, and then another for named after the game (ex. Local storage>Dolphin>GCN>Skies of Arcadia Legends) and then extract each game to the corresponding folder. Files formated as .iso or .GCM do not need to be extracted. If you need an archiving software look up rar or 7zip. Hope this helps.

title: Phones aren't really ready
comment: For all the people complaining about it running slow on even the top phones, it's because phone/tablet cpu's  simply don't have enough power to run emulated games smoothly.  Dolphin requires higher end desktop/laptop processors to run these types of emulations at their intended speed.  The top of the line phone cpu's are the equivalent of the mid range laptop cpu's,  thus the slow gameplay is created.

title: Still alpha
comment: At least provide small updates so that we think its under progess

I'm not using it ATM on my Nexus 5 because I know it will be terrible, but just to note, even the best gaming Android tablet (Tegra K1 devices) will be a little laggy. Tegra k1 devices even have dedicated video ram and more, and so far they lag to. There is no way open gl 2 will run this properly, so stop asking. I'm guessing this is up right now because this is their entry for making it work on the android platform, for the future devices actually capable of running this. In most instances, to emulate something requires way more resources. For console emulation many require from 2 to 4 times the hardware specs to emulate them. That is because of the strain of emulation. This is not the natural run environment, so it has to run many additional processes to make up for that. I think some time soon, GameCube will run smoothly, and that could be another year, maybe 2 years for Wii. AMD may get in the game and nVidia should be competing hard at that point, plus many upcoming hardware devs. I'm excited for the future of mobile computing/gaming

title: Pretty good, can't wait for future updates.
comment: I've currently been playing some games on the Nvidia Shield Tablet, and the performance is really good considering it's a $299 tablet! There are games that actually run really well, and others are getting really close to being able to play at full speed. I'm sure with the next-most powerful tablet along with a better build of the emulator will be able to get more games running at close to full speed.  There's only one reason why I'm not giving this a 5 star review, the options seem a bit lacking at the moment. I would personally like to see a frame-skipping option, so that audio would be better and improved emulation speed. With frame-skipping, I would be able to run Super Smash Bros. Melee at 30fps but with better sound and at a better speed. That being said, seeing as how this emulator is still in Alpha and Dolphin on PC has a frame-skip option, I'll assume that the option will be added at a later date.

title: Amazing potential
comment: Obviously the emulator doesn't run games full speed yet, even on the most powerful tablets. I have an Nvidia shield tablet, which has a quad core 2.2ghz cpu  - tegra K1.   I said I'd really push the emulator. I downloaded Metroid Prime for gamecube, and I got 10-12 fps CONSTANT. It was very stable, and the framerate never really dropped - when little or no rendering was necessary, or even when there was much more going on. It seemed that there wasn't a huge correlation between the amount of objects on screen and the framerate - for this device anyway.   This spells huge potential for me. With some more optimisation, who knows how well the developers can get games running. It' already not too bad!   Buy the paid version and support!

title: Performance depends on devices
comment: When I compare performance rates, I can say that device using Qualcomm chips are not optimized for this emulator and it causes lackluster performance because of the fact their drivers for the cpus are not up to date. For the best performance, I'd reccomend a device with a Tegra K1( dual-core may be better than a quad-core) since framerates on some games run decently around 40-50 fps at best in current devices, and in devices not released, some games can run at a full 60 fps. So this a wonderful achievement, and your criticism is stemmed from not having the best devices to run it, so support these guys and don't give them 1 star because it doesn't run on a device where it states it runs slow or doesn't support Open GL ES 3.0.

The running device should be at least 4 times more powerful than the device it is emulating, and it would help the developers if they had the gamecube source, which they don't. No one except Nintendo has it. So being able to even boot a rom is incredible. They are essentially writing a new console from scratch, with no guidelines. but for Android hardware. Give it a few years, and it might be a stable release. Thanks devs.

Ryan probably isn't rich people; he probably can't buy off contract the newest phones anytime he wants, thus, people who have bought those phones can test and see how it works. That is why this is on the Play Store and why he shouldn't take it down. This app has great potential, and I really think with enough time future devices like successors to the Note 3 and Xperia ZL may be able to run. title: Getting there
comment: 1star because a game doesn't load. Obviously you must not know what is required to emulate game architecture on another device that isn't optimized for it. For someone to be optimized for a GameCube you need at least twice the specs. At least 1.2 GHz. If I recall GameCube was 600 MHz. Not too mention the GPU has to be emulated as well. Oh yeah, don't forget textures have to display properly. So people, quit complaining and start sending error logs to the dev. Otherwise the dev won't know whats going.
